**Title:** design-portfolio

**Category:** forensics, steganography

**Description:**
A slick “design portfolio” site with curated color palettes… but something feels off.

I get this file:
```shell
file network_capture.pcap  
network_capture.pcap: pcap capture file, microsecond ts (little-endian) - version 2.4 (Ethernet, capture length 65535)
```

Open it in wireshark. There are `ssh`, `ftp`, `nbss`, `tcp`, and `http` packets in the file. 

I look at the `http` packets and in the headers I see `X-Flag-Total: 14` and `X-Flag-Chunk-0001: 89504E470D0A1A0A0000000D49484452...` 

I can see with the filter `frame.len > 6000` that 4 packets contain the 14 flag chunks.

I copy the header contents straight from wireshark with copy > value. Put each value in cyberchef with no whitespace and no new lines. I could automate extracting the flag chunks but its faster to do it this way. When I pulled these values with tshark (`tshark -r network_capture.pcap -Y "http" -V | grep "X-Flag-Chunk"`) the displayed values are truncated because of the size. Do the recipe from hex then render image to get the flag: [https://gchq.github.io/CyberChef/#recipe=From_Hex('None')Render_Image('Raw')&input=...](https://gchq.github.io/CyberChef/#recipe=From_Hex('None')Render_Image('Raw')&&oeol=CR)
